The Registrar of Societies&rsquo; insistence that the churches provide audited accounts to the government should be supported.The churches are largely not-for-profit entities that have been tax exempt for decades. But some have investments that generate rental income, for instance.Read:Church to fight law on financial auditThe Kenya National Congress of Pentecostal Churches and Ministries is in a confrontation with the government over requirements to attach audited accounts to annual returns to be filed with the registrar of the societies.Armoured cash transit pickups with armed police escorts are to be seen entering and leaving church compounds in Nairobi on Sundays. Already, there are billion-shilling annual tithe collections.If a church collects Sh200 million and uses only Sh50 million, the rest is income and ought to be taxed.Mark 12-17 reads, &ldquo;Jesus said to them, &lsquo;Render to Caesar the things that are Caesar&rsquo;s, and to God the things that are God&rsquo;s.&rsquo; And they marvelled at him.&rdquo;The Church in Kenya should pay taxes on its earnings. It is good for transparency.